        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We expect non-thermal polarised (synchrotron) continuum emission from a pointlike source within few arcsec of the center of the FOV. 

Using several known objects (flare stars, magnetars, and BH binaries) as a prototype (see science justification text), we arrive at an estimated minimum flux of this unknown object of 0.03 mJy. We therefore ask for an RMS sensitivity of 0.0075 mJy for a 4 sigma detection. The estimated necessary total obs. time for this is 5.6 h. 


</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We would already achieve  our science goal by detecting the source, measuring its continuum flux, and showing that it is polarised. However, should also the thermal emission of a potential M- or L-type stellar companion be bright enough for detection (not required to achieve out science goal), then the TDM spectral resultion will be perfectly sufficient to make a coarse assessment of the spectrum.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The extended configuration we are requesting will minimise shadowing for this observation at a relatively low elevation (41 deg max). 
It will also enable us to put at least loose constraints on the separation of potential binary companions if the object is nearby: The resolution of 0.4 arcsec corresponds to 0.2 AU at 5 pc, 2 AU at 50 pc. For comparison the separation of UV Cet is 0.6 AU.
Since we expect no extended emission but one or two pointlike objects, the observation could also be carried out higher angular resolution if the requested RMS is still achieved.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
