    <prp:code></prp:code>
    <prp:abstract>Nearly all Gamma Ray Bursts (GRBs) have either a known extragalactic host galaxy or no known host at all. One event in the overall Swift GRB sample (ca. 600 GRBs), however, was found to be a galactic object mimicking a GRB (Castro Tirado et al. 2008). This particular galactic GRB-like source SWIFT J195509.6+261406 displayed a fast rise exponential decay (FRED) gamma-ray lightcurve and is believed to be a compact binary or an isolated compact object such as a Magnetar at a few kpc.

Tello et al. (2013) have shown that it is highly likely that the present Swift GRB catalog is contaminated by galactic sources (ca. 3%) similar to SWIFT J195509.6+261406, which in turn are highly correlated with that subset of GRBs which features FRED lightcurves. Tello et al. therefore suggest that all galactic GRB-like sources may look like FRED GRBs to the observer.

In order to test this hypothesis and learn more about the nature of the counterparts of this hidden population of  "galactic GRBs", we propose to use ALMA to examine a specially selected set of FRED GRBs from the Swift Catalogue. In this first part of the project, we start by studying the prototype object SWIFT J195509.6+261406.

</prp:abstract>
